Playlists.Name: 808: The Playlist
Playlists.Description: The Roland TR-808 drum machine was intended to give studio musicians a simple tool for making backbeats. Instead, it kickstarted a revolution—one whose story is captured in full by the documentary 808, as well as these tracks. Beastie Boys flipped the 808's icy beats in reverse to make “Paul Revere”; Shannon's freestyle pop breakout “Let the Music Play” is propelled by its gently swung kicks and snares; and Afrika Bambaataa's formative electro hip-hop classic “Planet Rock” thrives on its throbbing thuds and crisp hi-hats.

Playlists.Name: Best of Glitch
Playlists.Description: In the late '90s, several electronic producers and artists began to embrace the unpredictability of technology, using faulty software and skipping CDs to create a new sound known as glitch. While some pieces by artists like Oval and Christian Fennesz are as abstract as can be, other acts like Farben and SND have used this twitchy approach to augment their experiments in danceable house and techno.

Playlists.Name: Cocteau Twins: Next Steps
Playlists.Description: With the swirling guitar wizardry of Robin Guthrie and the ethereal vocals of Elizabeth Fraser, the Cocteau Twins helped to invent dream pop in the '80s, becoming one of the decade's key indie rock bands. Their signature sound is unmistakable, but these deep cuts reveal a band with more range than their reputation suggests, moving from starkly dramatic goth rock to gentle ambient pop.

Playlists.Name: Concrete Riddims
Playlists.Description: Just because they're making experimental music doesn't mean that today's electronic artists can't also make you dance. Forward-thinking acts like Autechre, Diamond Version, Clark and Caribou maintain a perfect balance of body-rocking beats with edgy sounds and dissonant elements. Add the right touch of cacophony for your next dance party or tap into a beat-driven pulse to get you through the day.

Playlists.Name: Dance Remixes Essentials
Playlists.Description: Dance remixes are almost as old as modern dance music itself. They were born with ’70s disco, as producers like Tom Moulton, Walter Gibbons, and Larry Levan supplemented multitrack magic with techniques borrowed from Jamaican dub—echo, panning, delay, phasing—in order to stretch three-minute songs into dance-floor epics. Since then, dance remixes have proven one of popular music’s most productive forms of cross-pollination, decade after decade. In the ’90s, remixers like Andrew Weatherall and Pet Shop Boys wrung throbbing club classics out of psychedelic rock and sneering Britpop, while Todd Terry and Armand van Helden made unexpected floor-fillers out of acoustic art-pop. In the ’00s, remixes sparked a chain reaction of rock/rave fusions, and the anything-goes spirit of mashups mimicked the nonlinear logic of the internet. Since then, savvy remixes have bridged chart pop and EDM, lent indie cred to major stars, and offered playgrounds for producers to try out new styles and invent new subgenres.

Playlists.Name: Popol Vuh Essentials
Playlists.Description: German electronic pioneers Popol Vuh drew from ancient culture and spirituality to inform their unique brand of ambient music. Formed in '69 by keyboardist Florian Fricke, the band were among the first to utilise the Moog synthesiser, constructing transcendental electronic soundscapes while also employing an exotic array of instruments to create a union of the earthly and the ethereal. Director Werner Herzog later tapped the group to perform soundtracks for many of his best known films, including Aguirre, The Wrath of God and Fitzcarraldo.

Playlists.Name: TR-808 classics: Celebrating the famous drum machine
Playlists.Description: Roland's unmistakable TR-808 is the world's most loved drum machine. Discover 15 classic 808 tracks, from Egyptian Lover and Cybotron to Young Jeezy and Kanye West.
